# DreggNet STAGING — reverse proxy + DREGG-CAPABILITY forward-auth gate + the
# public portal.
#
# Two public faces:
#   - portal.example.com  — the PUBLIC, read-only web portal (no auth): the live
#     cell network view + the trustless cell cards (light-client verify in the tab).
#     Static files from /srv/portal; its /api/* + /observability/* are proxied to the
#     DREGG NODE's read surface (`dregg-node:8420`, public, read-only) — the data
#     backbone, NOT the Discord bot, so the public viewer is independent of the bot's
#     lifecycle (the bot can be down and the portal still reads the live network).
#   - dreggnet.example.com — the gated operator surface (gateway machines API +
#     the bot's /admin webportal), gated by a dregg CAPABILITY.
#
# AUTH IS DREGG-NATIVE (no passwords). The gated surfaces are protected by
# `forward_auth` to the `webauth` service (dreggnet-webauth on :8099): Caddy calls
# its /auth once per request; the operator's dregg capability (a `dga1_…` token
# held in their cipherclerk, presented via the session cookie set by the login
# flow) is verified OFFLINE against the surface's required capability — 2xx admit
# / 401 (browsers are bounced to the dregg login page). Capabilities attenuate:
# a `grafana-view` capability can never reach `ops-admin`. A BREAK-GLASS override
# (DREGG_WEBAUTH_BREAK_GLASS on the webauth service, presented in the
# X-Dregg-Break-Glass header) admits regardless, so we are never locked out if
# the cap flow breaks. Bootstrap a root authority + caps with `dregg-authctl`
# (see docker-compose.yml `webauth`).

# The dregg login flow — PUBLIC (no auth) so a denied user CAN sign in. Imported
# into every gated host. Caddy strips the `/.dregg-auth` prefix (chosen to not
# collide with grafana's own /login), so webauth serves /login, /logout, /healthz.
(dregg_login) {
	handle_path /.dregg-auth/* {
		reverse_proxy webauth:8099
	}
}

# SUBJECT-SPOOFING DEFENCE. Every identity-gated upstream (console / attach / …)
# trusts X-Dregg-Subject (the cap holder) / X-Dregg-Cap / X-Dregg-Auth as the
# VERIFIED identity webauth set. That trust is sound ONLY if a CLIENT cannot
# supply those headers. The webauth forward_auth `copy_headers` overwrites them on
# the ADMIT path, but a path where webauth admits WITHOUT re-setting one (or any
# future bypass) would otherwise let a forged value survive. So we DELETE every
# client-supplied identity/break-glass header BEFORE the auth subrequest runs —
# the upstream sees only webauth-set values, never a forgery. Import this inside
# the gated `handle` block, ahead of `forward_auth`.
#
# PRIVATE UPSTREAM (the second must): the gated upstreams (console:8097,
# attach:8100, …) MUST be reachable ONLY from Caddy over the private docker
# network — NO host port-publish. Anything that can hit them directly sets every
# header freely and impersonates any subject, bypassing this strip entirely. Keep
# them off `ports:` in docker-compose (expose to the compose network only).
(dregg_strip_forged_identity) {
	request_header -X-Dregg-Subject
	request_header -X-Dregg-Cap
	request_header -X-Dregg-Auth
	request_header -X-Dregg-Break-Glass
}

{
	# ACME contact for Let's Encrypt issuance on the real domains.
	email admin@example.com
	# Clients that connect by raw IP send no TLS SNI; present the internal-CA
	# `localhost` cert by default so https://<EDGE_HOST>/ still handshakes
	# before the real domain certs land.
	default_sni localhost
	# On-demand TLS for the published minisites (`*.example.com`). A wildcard
	# cert would need a DNS-01 challenge (a Caddy DNS-provider plugin + an API
	# token for wherever example.com is hosted, neither wired here), so instead
	# Caddy mints a REAL per-name Let's Encrypt cert over HTTP-01 the first time
	# a concrete `<name>.example.com` is requested. `ask` gates issuance: Caddy
	# asks the gateway whether `<name>` is a published site before obtaining a
	# cert, so only real sites mint certs (Let's Encrypt rate-limit hygiene). The
	# wildcard DNS `*.example.com -> <EDGE_HOST>` makes the HTTP-01 challenge
	# reach this box.
	on_demand_tls {
		ask http://gateway:8080/internal/site-exists
	}
}

# --- the PUBLISHED MINISITES (*.example.com) -------------------------------
# Every published minisite cell, served by the gateway's SiteHostHandler. NO
# basic-auth: a published public site is served to anyone (the publish was the
# cap-gated step; reads are free). The gateway resolves the request's Host to the
# site cell and serves the asset. TLS is on-demand (per-name Let's Encrypt over
# HTTP-01, gated by the gateway `ask` above) since a wildcard cert needs DNS-01.
*.example.com {
	tls {
		on_demand
	}
	encode gzip
	reverse_proxy gateway:8080
}

# --- the PUBLIC portal -----------------------------------------------------
# portal.example.com — the public face of DreggNet. NO basic-auth: this is the
# read-mostly portal anyone can open to SEE the live network and trustlessly
# verify a cell in their own browser (the wasm light client under /pkg). Automatic
# HTTPS (Let's Encrypt, HTTP-01 over :80) issues once the A-record
# `portal.example.com -> <EDGE_HOST>` propagates; until then the :443 fallback
# cert keeps it reachable by IP for testing (`curl -k --resolve`).
#
# RUNBOOK: after the A-record lands, `docker compose restart caddy` to clear any
# ACME backoff so the real cert issues promptly.
portal.example.com {
	encode gzip
	# GW-4a defence-in-depth: the custodial signing endpoint /api/op is NEVER
	# served on the PUBLIC (no-auth) portal. The public /api/* now proxies to the
	# read-only dregg node (which has no /api/op at all), so this 403 is pure
	# belt-and-suspenders — even if /api/* were ever repointed at the bot again, an
	# unauthenticated POST /api/op can never reach a custodial signer through the
	# public proxy. The custodial /api/op stays reachable only on the cap-gated
	# operator surface (dreggnet.example.com) and the in-process desktop drive
	# path. A more-specific matcher wins over /api/* below.
	@apiop path /api/op /api/op/*
	handle @apiop {
		respond "custodial /api/op is not publicly accessible" 403
	}
	# The read API the portal's JS calls (public, read-only) → the DREGG NODE
	# (`dregg-node:8420`), the live-network data backbone: /api/cells,
	# /api/cell/<id>, /api/federations, and the /observability/stream SSE liveness
	# feed (hello + 15s pings) the index's "live" badge listens for. The portal is
	# thus DECOUPLED from the Discord bot — the bot is NO LONGER load-bearing for the
	# public viewer (it can be down and the portal still reads the live network). The
	# node's read routes (`node/src/api.rs` `public_routes`) carry the same
	# /api/cells + /api/cell/<id> shapes the portal renders, plus the drive layer's
	# node ingress (/api/turns/submit-signed, /api/faucet, /api/node/identity) the bot
	# never served. The custodial /api/op is still refused above (the node has no such
	# endpoint; the 403 stays as belt-and-suspenders).
	handle /api/* {
		reverse_proxy dregg-node:8420
	}
	handle /observability/* {
		reverse_proxy dregg-node:8420 {
			# SSE: stream events through without buffering.
			flush_interval -1
		}
	}
	# Everything else → the baked static portal (index.html, cell.html, the wasm
	# light-client bundle under /pkg). Mounted read-only by the caddy service.
	handle {
		root * /srv/portal
		try_files {path} /index.html
		file_server
	}
}

# --- the CUSTOMER-FACING public faces (landing · status · console) ---------
# REVIEWED-GO live-edge deploy for the customer cloud face. The three crates
# (`dreggnet-landing`, `dreggnet-status`, `dreggnet-console`) are pure-std HTTP
# servers, deploy-ready and env-configured; bringing them live is (1) these
# vhosts, (2) the matching compose services (below in docker-compose.yml:
# landing:8096, status:8095, console:8097), and (3) the public A-records. Until
# the DNS lands the raw-IP fallback block at the bottom keeps them reachable for
# smoke testing. This step COORDINATES WITH the public gateway deploy.

# example.com (apex) — the PUBLIC FRONT DOOR. No auth: what the verifiable agent
# cloud IS, the live status (embedded client-side from status.example.com), and
# the deploy/run/verify quickstart. Env: LANDING_STATUS_URL + LANDING_CONSOLE_URL
# point at the real public hosts so the live banner + sign-in link resolve.
example.com {
	encode gzip
	reverse_proxy landing:8096
}

# status.example.com — the PUBLIC STATUS PAGE. No auth (anyone can check "is the
# cloud up?"). The LiveSource reads the real n=5 federation behind STATUS_NODE_URL
# (dregg-node:8420) + the gateway/bridge/economy surfaces; an unreachable surface
# renders Unknown, never falsely green. Also serves /status.json for embedding.
status.example.com {
	encode gzip
	reverse_proxy status:8095
}

# console.example.com — the SIGNED-IN CUSTOMER CONSOLE. GATED by a `console-user`
# dregg capability via the webauth forward-auth: Caddy verifies the cap and copies
# the resolved X-Dregg-Subject (the cap holder = the cell owner) onto the upstream,
# and the console cap-scopes every surface to exactly that subject. The LiveSource
# reads the real resource surfaces behind CONSOLE_READ_API; a user only ever sees
# their own cells (the cap-scoping teeth). `tls internal` until the A-record lands.
console.example.com {
	tls internal
	# PUBLIC: the dregg login flow (so a denied user can sign in).
	import dregg_login
	# GATED: everything else needs a `console-user` dregg capability. The verified
	# subject is copied on as X-Dregg-Subject — the console NEVER trusts a param.
	handle {
		# Strip any client-forged identity headers BEFORE the auth subrequest, so
		# only webauth-set values reach console:8097 (which MUST be Caddy-private).
		import dregg_strip_forged_identity
		forward_auth webauth:8099 {
			uri /auth?cap=console-user
			copy_headers X-Dregg-Subject X-Dregg-Cap X-Dregg-Auth
		}
		reverse_proxy console:8097
	}
}

# attach.example.com — the PORTAL WEB ATTACH (the web twin of the SSH attach).
# REVIEWED-GO (the live edge): UNCOMMENT once (1) the `dreggnet-attach` service is
# in docker-compose (env: ATTACH_REQUIRE_CAP=attach-user, ATTACH_LOGIN_BASE=
# /.dregg-auth, ATTACH_LIVE_BACKEND=<hosted-session backend>, ATTACH_BIND=:8100),
# and (2) the `attach.example.com -> <EDGE_HOST>` A-record lands. GATED exactly
# like the console: the webauth forward-auth verifies an `attach-user` cap and
# copies the resolved X-Dregg-Subject onto the upstream; the attach cap-scopes
# every session to that subject (a user drives + streams + verifies ONLY their own
# hosted agent). The shipped binary serves a demo-planner session out of the box;
# the live Hermes/Kimi brain over a confined workdir is the ATTACH_LIVE_BACKEND swap.
#
# SECURITY (subject-spoofing): the attach trusts X-Dregg-Subject as the verified
# identity. That trust is ONLY sound if a CLIENT cannot supply it. Two musts before
# this goes live:
#   (1) STRIP the inbound auth headers so only webauth-set values reach the upstream
#       — delete any client-supplied X-Dregg-Subject / X-Dregg-Cap / X-Dregg-Auth /
#       X-Dregg-Break-Glass BEFORE forward_auth (a `request_header` deletion that runs
#       ahead of the auth subrequest). copy_headers overwrites on the admit path, but
#       a path where webauth admits WITHOUT re-setting the header would otherwise let
#       a forged value survive.
#   (2) the `attach:8100` upstream MUST be reachable ONLY from Caddy (private docker
#       network / no host port-publish) — anything that can hit :8100 directly sets
#       every header freely and impersonates any subject.
# Set ATTACH_BREAK_GLASS to a strong secret (or leave it UNSET to disable break-glass
# entirely) — the app no longer honors a plain `X-Dregg-Auth: break-glass` header.
# attach.example.com {
# 	tls internal
# 	import dregg_login
# 	handle {
# 		# (1) strip client-forged identity headers before the auth subrequest
# 		#     (the shared snippet — same defence the live console route uses).
# 		import dregg_strip_forged_identity
# 		forward_auth webauth:8099 {
# 			uri /auth?cap=attach-user
# 			copy_headers X-Dregg-Subject X-Dregg-Cap X-Dregg-Auth
# 		}
# 		# (2) attach:8100 MUST be Caddy-private (no host port-publish) — see the
# 		#     dregg_strip_forged_identity note.
# 		reverse_proxy attach:8100
# 	}
# }

# --- the gated operator domain --------------------------------------------
# Automatic HTTPS (Let's Encrypt, HTTP-01 over :80) kicks in once the plain
# A-record `dreggnet.example.com -> <EDGE_HOST>` propagates from the
# example.com registrar. Until then Caddy keeps retrying issuance in the
# background and the :443 self-signed fallback below keeps the stack reachable
# by IP.
dreggnet.example.com {
	# PUBLIC: the dregg login flow (sign in with your capability).
	import dregg_login
	# GATED: everything else needs a `gateway-admin` dregg capability. forward_auth
	# (auth phase) runs before the inner handles route. DEFENCE IN DEPTH: the cap
	# gate here AND the bot's ADMIN_TOKEN underneath (Bearer/`?token=`).
	handle {
		forward_auth webauth:8099 {
			uri /auth?cap=gateway-admin
			copy_headers X-Dregg-Subject X-Dregg-Cap X-Dregg-Auth
		}
		# The Discord bot's `/admin` webportal (its axum server on :8080).
		handle /admin* {
			reverse_proxy dreggnet-discord-bot:8080
		}
		# Everything else → the httpe gateway (the fly-compatible machines API).
		handle {
			reverse_proxy gateway:8080
		}
	}
}

# --- the OPS/ADMIN dashboard (SEPARATE, stronger admin password) -----------
# ops.dreggnet.example.com — the operator's single pane of glass over the
# whole DreggNet cloud (the `dreggnet-ops` aggregator on :8090). This is the
# admin-only surface, gated by an `ops-admin` dregg CAPABILITY (held in the
# operator's cipherclerk; NOT the same as a `grafana-view` cap — attenuation
# keeps them distinct). Defence in depth: this block is the ONLY route to the
# ops dashboard, and the cap gate is independent of the operator surface.
#
# TLS: `tls internal` (Caddy's self-signed CA) so the dashboard is reachable by
# IP BEFORE the `ops.dreggnet.example.com` A-record propagates — test the
# break-glass path with:
#   curl -k --resolve ops.dreggnet.example.com:443:<EDGE_HOST> \
#     -H "X-Dregg-Break-Glass: <DREGG_WEBAUTH_BREAK_GLASS>" \
#     https://ops.dreggnet.example.com/healthz
# RUNBOOK: once the A-record lands, drop `tls internal` to switch to Let's Encrypt.
ops.dreggnet.example.com {
	tls internal
	# PUBLIC: the dregg login flow.
	import dregg_login
	# GATED: the ops dashboard needs an `ops-admin` dregg capability.
	handle {
		forward_auth webauth:8099 {
			uri /auth?cap=ops-admin
			copy_headers X-Dregg-Subject X-Dregg-Cap X-Dregg-Auth
		}
		reverse_proxy ops:8090
	}
}

# --- headscale control + DERP endpoint -------------------------------------
# The self-hosted Tailscale control server for the DreggNet private mesh. NO
# basic_auth here — tailscale clients authenticate with the headscale Noise
# protocol + pre-auth keys, and a basic-auth gate would break them. Caddy
# terminates TLS and reverse-proxies the control protocol AND the embedded DERP
# relay (websockets, handled transparently) to the headscale container.
# Automatic HTTPS (Let's Encrypt, HTTP-01) issues once the A-record
# `headscale.dreggnet.example.com -> <EDGE_HOST>` propagates; the whole
# mesh comes online at that point (the same DNS gate the rest of staging waits on).
headscale.dreggnet.example.com {
	reverse_proxy headscale:8080
}

# --- the OBSERVABILITY Grafana (admin-login gated) -------------------------
# grafana.dreggnet.example.com — provisioned dashboards over Prometheus.
# Grafana sits on the external `dreggnet_default` network (the dreggnet-obs
# stack attaches to it), so Caddy reaches it in-cluster as `grafana:3000`.
# Gated by a `grafana-view` dregg CAPABILITY at the edge (defence in depth:
# Grafana's own login still sits underneath). `tls internal` until the A-record
# `grafana.dreggnet.example.com -> <EDGE_HOST>` propagates — then drop
# the `tls internal` line for an automatic Let's Encrypt cert. Prometheus and
# Alertmanager intentionally get NO public vhost (loopback + SSH tunnel only).
grafana.dreggnet.example.com {
	tls internal
	# PUBLIC: the dregg login flow (under /.dregg-auth — Grafana keeps its own /login).
	import dregg_login
	# GATED: a `grafana-view` dregg capability.
	handle {
		forward_auth webauth:8099 {
			uri /auth?cap=grafana-view
			copy_headers X-Dregg-Subject X-Dregg-Cap X-Dregg-Auth
		}
		reverse_proxy grafana:3000
	}
}

# --- raw-IP / pre-DNS fallback ---------------------------------------------
# Caddy's internal CA (self-signed) so the auth-gated stack is reachable by IP
# (https://<EDGE_HOST>/) before the public certs land. The names are listed
# explicitly so the internal CA has subjects to issue for. Test with `curl -k`.
# The portal is also served here at /portal-preview/* for pre-DNS smoke testing by
# raw IP (the public host block above is the real entry once DNS lands).
<EDGE_HOST>, localhost {
	tls internal
	# Pre-DNS portal preview by raw IP: serve the SAME static portal here so it can
	# be smoke-tested before portal.example.com resolves. The portal's read API is
	# also reachable by raw IP through the gated path below (dregg cap), but the
	# public, no-auth path is portal.example.com once DNS lands.
	handle_path /portal-preview/* {
		root * /srv/portal
		try_files {path} /index.html
		file_server
	}
	# PUBLIC: the dregg login flow (reachable by raw IP pre-DNS too).
	import dregg_login
	# GATED: the gateway-admin dregg capability. By raw IP pre-DNS, present the
	# break-glass token (no Host-based cap mapping resolves for a bare IP, so the
	# explicit ?cap=gateway-admin below is what the cap check uses):
	#   curl -k -H "X-Dregg-Break-Glass: <token>" https://<EDGE_HOST>/admin?token=<ADMIN_TOKEN>
	handle {
		forward_auth webauth:8099 {
			uri /auth?cap=gateway-admin
			copy_headers X-Dregg-Subject X-Dregg-Cap X-Dregg-Auth
		}
		# The Discord bot's `/admin` webportal.
		handle /admin* {
			reverse_proxy dreggnet-discord-bot:8080
		}
		handle {
			reverse_proxy gateway:8080
		}
	}
}
